In .NET MAUI, the `Window` class exposes these lifecycle events:

- **Created** – window created
- **Activated** – gained focus
- **Deactivated** – lost focus
- **Stopped** – no longer visible
- **Resumed** – visible again after stop
- **Destroying** – being torn down
- **Backgrounding** – going to background (iOS/Mac Catalyst)

### Example: Subscribe in `CreateWindow`

Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(">>> Window Created");
        window.Activated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(">>> Window Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(">>> Window Deactivated");
        window.Stopped += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(">>> Window Stopped");
        window.Resumed += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(">>> Window Resumed");
        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(">>> Window Destroying");
        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(">>> Window Backgrounding");

        return window;
    }
}
```

Output appears in the **Debug** output window (Visual Studio → View → Output → select "Debug").

> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` only fires on iOS/Mac Catalyst. On Android/Windows the equivalent transition raises `Stopped`.
